<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1940-07-13T14:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1940-07-13T14:00:00-05:00" n="972" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d972">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">822.796/192: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in Ecuador</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Long</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Quito</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-07-13T14:00:00-05:00">July 13, 1940—2
                                p.m.</date><lb/>[Received 9 p.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>155. After a long conference with President-elect who arrived Quito
                            yesterday, he states that he favors introduction of services by Panagra
                            as outlined by the Department: That he is not in favor of arbitrary
                            cancellation of any contract but thinks that study might reveal
                            violations by Sedta. Investigation is being made now. Please refer to my
                            telegram No. 144, July 9, 6 p.m. and 146, July 10, 10 a.m.<note n="15" xml:id="d972fn1">Latter not printed.</note></p>
                        <p>In any event the question of financing the elimination remains.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Long</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>